metadata.name: Daydreamer #159
metadata.description:
‘For the artist communication with nature remains the most essential condition. The artist is human, himself nature; part of nature within natural space.’ (Paul Klee, 1944) 


Working on long-form nature has an interesting side effect. On the one hand, you're attempting a shallow imitation of a landscape.... You are working with cold logic and code, vainly trying to control randomness to create this virtual facsimile, something you know is artificial.... 

....and yet.... even with all this left-brain activity, your right-brain pushes back, and imagines being there. While working on this project I found myself continually daydreaming, wandering off to hear the sounds of waterfalls, or the crunch of walking along a sandy lake shore. If you've ever wondered about coding, I urge you to learn. Daydreams await....


Press '1' once rendering is finished, to redraw at 5120x5120 resolution 
Press '2' to export without post-processing effects 

3rd party libraries (license text and links included in source) 
- p5.js - Creative coding framework 
- JS Topology Suite "JSTS", a port of Java Topology Suite "JTS" - High-level Geometry library 
- WebGLImageFilter, Dominic Szablewski - phoboslab.org 

I have tried to use soft blurs and shadows to give a sense of layering and depth to the scene. After viewing for a while, it reminds me of 3D paper-art. There are traits for colour and amount of birds, waterfalls, etc. but none are especially rare – These properties are intended for filtering the collection.

objkt.name: Ode to Bugs and Happy Accidents #220

metadata.name: Ode to Bugs and Happy Accidents #220
metadata.description:
“If debugging is the process of removing software bugs, then programming must be the process of putting them in.”

― Edsger W. Dijkstra


This artwork is dedicated to happy accidents, mistakes, and bugs. Every key part of it is based on some sort of failure: wrong variable value, unstopped recursion, untimely function call. And sometimes it leads to pleasant results.

It was created to celebrate #fxhashturnsone event.

The earnings are partly donated to:
- Processing Foundation
- #TezosStandsWithUkraine

[a] - toggle animation
[1] - save PNG in low resolution
[2] - save PNG in medium resolution
[3] - save PNG in high resolution
[4] - save PNG in ultra-high resolution

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js

By Collapsar Beauty

metadata.name: Silent Marsh #23
metadata.description:
Naturalism is the only art school faithful to nature among the visual arts. Including a descriptive painting of nature and minimally altered human figures.
The fidelity to nature gives the piece a photographic feel.
Like other painting schools, this style was heavily influenced by the (aesthetics) and (culture) of different regions.
Here, the only question is:
Is it possible for a painting to be completely naturalistic without the artist creating and reflecting his thoughts?

This collection represents our mental image of nature, which is implemented by code.

metadata.name: Flowers #181
metadata.description:
This project is inspired by natural flowers.
Flowers and foliage in the piece are arranged randomly, but they follow a regular pattern, as flowers do as they grow.
Initially, flowers are produced randomly and without color. Afterwards, the pieces are painted according to the color palettes, so that viewers can feel the effect of colors.
Each piece is processed until the frame part is reached.

Fully generated by p5.js

Press 's' to get a 3000x3000 px PNG file.

metadata.name: Laniakea #192
metadata.description:
This piece captures the mysterious beauty of the Laniakea Supercluster, the colossal cosmic structure that contains our Milky Way galaxy.

A deep black backdrop is scattered with shimmering stars, evoking a sense of endless space and awe-inspiring expanse. Winds of dark matter are captured in the mid-ground, representing the invisible force that drives the formation of the galaxies within the Supercluster.

The foreground features a small spiral galaxy, shining brightly against the backdrop of the universe, reminding us that we are an integral part of an unimaginably grand structure.
